      <!-- Section 1: Definition -->
      <section id="definition" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>The GEO Definition</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Generative engine optimisation (GEO) is the practice of structuring content, entity signals, and technical infrastructure so that large language models cite your brand when generating answers.</strong>
          The term covers both the British spelling used throughout this guide and the American spelling — generative engine optimization — which dominates search volume. Both refer to the same discipline.
        </p>

        <p>
          When a user asks ChatGPT, Perplexity, Google AI Overviews, or Microsoft Copilot a question, those systems retrieve information from across the web, synthesise it into a coherent response, and cite the sources they drew from. The brands that appear as cited sources receive attention, authority, and traffic. GEO is the discipline of ensuring your brand is one of those sources — consistently, across all major models, for the queries that matter to your business.
        </p>

        <p>
          GEO is not a rebrand of <a href="/answer-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">answer engine optimisation (AEO)</a>, nor is it a synonym for SEO with "AI" appended. It is an additional discipline with its own framework, its own signals, and its own success metrics. Traditional SEO remains important — a strong domain authority and technical SEO foundation feed into GEO performance — but GEO introduces requirements that SEO alone does not address: entity definition, content citability architecture, and cross-model visibility testing.
        </p>

        <p>
          For the complete practitioner's framework, see the <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Generative Engine Optimisation pillar guide</a>. For a glossary-style breakdown of GEO alongside related terms, see the <a href="/geo-definition/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO definition page</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: How GEO Works -->
