        <h2>How GEO Works</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>GEO works by aligning your content with the retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) pipeline that AI search systems use to produce answers.</strong>
          Understanding this pipeline is the foundation of any effective GEO strategy.
        </p>

        <h3>The RAG Pipeline</h3>
        <p>
          Most AI search platforms — Google AI Overviews, Perplexity, Copilot — use a retrieval-augmented generation process. When a query arrives, the system does not rely solely on its pre-trained knowledge. Instead, it retrieves relevant documents from the web (or a curated index), extracts specific passages from those documents, and synthesises them into a single generated response. The page that provides the clearest, most authoritative passage for a given sub-question gets cited.
        </p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Query interpretation.</strong> The model analyses the user's intent, identifies entities, and may decompose complex queries into sub-questions.</li>
          <li><strong>Source retrieval.</strong> The system searches its index using a combination of keyword matching and dense vector retrieval. Pages with strong entity signals and topical depth rank higher in retrieval.</li>
          <li><strong>Passage extraction.</strong> From retrieved documents, the model identifies the most relevant passages. Declarative sentences, specific data points, and clearly structured sections are preferentially extracted.</li>
          <li><strong>Synthesis and citation.</strong> The model combines passages into a coherent answer and cites the sources. Sources providing unique, authoritative content are cited as distinct sources rather than folded into a generic synthesis.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>The Role of Entity Authority</h3>
        <p>
          AI models maintain a knowledge graph — an internal network of entities (brands, people, concepts, organisations) and their relationships. Before a model decides whether to cite your brand, it evaluates whether your brand is a well-defined entity within that graph. Brands with consistent presence across Wikipedia, Wikidata, Google's Knowledge Panel, Crunchbase, LinkedIn, and major industry directories are treated as authoritative entities. Those that exist only on their own website are treated as low-authority sources, and are frequently omitted from AI-generated answers even when their content is directly relevant.
        </p>

        <p>
          Building entity authority is therefore a foundational GEO requirement — separate from, and preceding, any content optimisation work. For a step-by-step explanation of the full mechanism, see our guide to <a href="/how-geo-works/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">how GEO works</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

