        <h2>What Makes Content Citable</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Citability is a structural property of content, not just a quality property — AI models extract passages, not whole pages, and those passages must be self-contained, declarative, and factually distinctive to be selected.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>Declarative Section Openings</h3>
        <p>
          Every major section should open with a sentence that directly defines or asserts the key claim of that section. The format "X is Y" or "X works by doing Z" gives the AI model an extractable, attributable statement. Sections that open with preamble ("In this section, we will explore...") are less likely to be cited because the model cannot extract a clean, quotable passage from them.
        </p>

        <h3>Original Data and Specific Claims</h3>
        <p>
          If every page on a topic says broadly the same thing, AI models synthesise a generic answer without citing any specific source. Content that provides a unique data point — a specific statistic, a named case, a precise benchmark — gives the model a reason to attribute that claim. Original data is the highest-value GEO content asset because it cannot be obtained from any other source.
        </p>

        <h3>Entity-Rich References</h3>
        <p>
          Content that explicitly connects concepts to recognised entities — named tools, named organisations, named standards — signals to AI systems that the content is grounded in the real world rather than generic. Named entity density is a quality signal for LLMs in the same way that specific, cited sources are quality signals for human readers.
        </p>

        <h3>Structured Data</h3>
        <p>
          JSON-LD schema markup — particularly Article, FAQPage, and HowTo — provides machine-readable metadata that reduces ambiguity during retrieval. Schema does not guarantee citation, but it reduces the risk of a model misinterpreting your content type, misattributing your claims, or skipping your page entirely during the retrieval stage. The <a href="/generative-search-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative search optimisation</a> technical guide covers schema implementation in full.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6: Who Needs GEO -->
      <section id="who-needs-geo" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Who Needs GEO?</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Any organisation that depends on organic search visibility for leads, revenue, or reputation needs a GEO strategy — the shift from link-based search to AI-generated answers is already underway and accelerating.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>B2B and SaaS Companies</h3>
        <p>
          B2B buyers use AI assistants to conduct early-stage vendor research. When a procurement team member asks "what are the best project management tools for distributed teams?", the brands cited in the response enter the consideration set before any human-authored shortlist is compiled. For SaaS companies, AI citation is becoming the new analyst quadrant — appearing in AI-generated answers confers authority that influences pipeline.
        </p>

        <h3>Professional Services</h3>
        <p>
          Law firms, consultancies, accountancies, and agencies are directly affected by AI-generated recommendation lists. AI search already answers queries like "best employment lawyers in London" or "top digital marketing agencies UK" by synthesising information from across the web. Professional services firms without entity authority in knowledge bases are consistently absent from those lists, regardless of how well their website ranks in traditional blue links.
        </p>

        <h3>E-commerce</h3>
        <p>
          Product discovery is moving from search results pages to AI-assisted recommendation flows. When a user asks "best running shoes for flat feet," an AI-generated response citing specific products and retailers drives consideration without the user ever visiting a results page. E-commerce GEO focuses on product entity markup, review aggregation, and associating your brand with category-level queries.
        </p>

        <h3>Content Publishers and Media</h3>
        <p>
          Publishers whose business model depends on organic traffic face acute pressure as AI answers reduce the click-through rate from informational queries. GEO for publishers focuses on building source citation authority — ensuring that when AI systems synthesise content on a topic, they cite your publication as a source rather than using your content without attribution. Building that citation authority now, while the citation patterns are still forming, is significantly easier than reclaiming ground once competitors have established themselves as the go-to cited sources.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 7: Getting Started -->
      <section id="getting-started" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Getting Started with GEO</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The most practical starting point for GEO is an AI visibility audit — establishing a baseline of how your brand currently appears (or does not appear) across the major AI platforms for your target queries.</strong>
        </p>

        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Run a baseline citation audit.</strong> Manually query your top 20 target queries across ChatGPT, Perplexity, Microsoft Copilot, and Google AI Overviews. Record whether your brand is cited, how it is described, and which competitors appear instead. This baseline is the starting point for measuring GEO progress.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Audit your entity presence.</strong> Search for your brand on Wikipedia, Wikidata, Crunchbase, and LinkedIn. Identify gaps — if your brand lacks a Wikipedia entry, a Wikidata record, or a verified Google Knowledge Panel, entity building takes priority before content work begins.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Restructure priority content for citability.</strong> On your highest-traffic and most topically authoritative pages, revise section openings to lead with declarative statements. Add original data where you have it. Ensure headings match the exact phrasing of the questions users ask.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Implement and validate schema.</strong> Deploy Article and FAQPage JSON-LD on content pages. Validate using Google's Rich Results Test. Ensure author and publisher fields reference your organisation entity by <code>@id</code> rather than re-declaring inline.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Configure AI crawler access.</strong> Audit <code>robots.txt</code> to confirm AI crawlers (GPTBot, ClaudeBot, PerplexityBot, Google-Extended) have access to the content you want cited. Deploy an <code>llms.txt</code> file to provide a curated content index for AI systems.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Establish a monitoring cadence.</strong> Re-run your citation audit weekly for the first three months. Track changes in citation frequency, accuracy, and share of voice. Use the results to identify which content changes produced citation improvements.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          Our <a href="/geo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO services</a> cover each phase of this process end-to-end — from initial audit through to ongoing monitoring and competitive intelligence. If you want to understand your current AI search position before committing to a programme, <a href="/contact/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">get in touch</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

